## 1. Why This Outperforms Traditional ML

Traditional ML flood models (gradient-boosted trees, LSTMs, physics-based HEC-RAS/SWMM) have well-documented failure modes. This swarm is explicitly designed to exploit them.

### 1.1 The ML Failure Modes We Target

| ML Weakness | How This Swarm Addresses It |
|---|---|
| **Distribution shift** — trained on historical data, blind to novel compound events | Agents reason from first principles each run; no retraining needed when climate patterns shift |
| **Feature engineering bottleneck** — practitioners must hand-craft features | LLM agents extract implicit signals (e.g. warning text semantics, geographic correlations) without explicit features |
| **Black-box predictions** — stakeholders cannot audit decisions | Every agent emits a `reasoning` field; full decision trace is human-readable |
| **Single-point-of-failure** — one model, one failure mode | Five independent agents; synthesis layer detects and flags disagreement as a risk signal itself |
| **Threshold brittleness** — fixed alarm thresholds miss context | Agents cross-reference signals; 40mm/hr means different things at high tide vs low tide vs with a Black Rainstorm warning |
| **Temporal rigidity** — LSTMs need fixed lookback windows | Agents reason over variable-length context; can incorporate an unusual 3-week dry spell as context |
| **No common-sense** — ML cannot reason "this is September, typhoon season, historically 2019-type event" | LLMs carry climatological priors baked into pretraining; agents can be prompted to apply them |
| **Language barrier** — ML outputs are numbers, not directives | Swarm outputs bilingual (EN + TC) district-level narratives, confidence levels, and recommended actions |

### 1.2 The Compound Event Advantage — Our Core Thesis

> **Traditional ML treats features as independent inputs. The HK flooding problem is fundamentally about compound events — concurrent conditions that are individually manageable but catastrophic together.**

Hong Kong's worst flood events (Black Rainstorm 2023, Typhoon Hato 2017) were compound:

```
Black rain (WRAINB)
  + high astronomical tide (QUB tide gauge > 2.5m)
  + typhoon signal TC8+
  + saturated antecedent soil
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
  = catastrophic surface flooding + storm surge in low-lying areas
```

An LSTM treats these as four separate input channels. Our `CompoundDetector` agent specifically watches for dangerous co-occurrences and raises a `COMPOUND_EVENT` flag that overrides individual agent scores.

### 1.3 The Reasoning Transparency Advantage

Every prediction includes a full chain of thought. When the system issues a severity-9 warning, emergency managers can read: *"Rainfall agent detected 87mm/hr at Tuen Mun (RF019) and 72mm/hr at Tsuen Wan Ho Koon (RF018) — northwest NT corridor pattern consistent with orographic enhancement from southwest airflow. Tide agent confirms spring tide peak at QUB (+2.7m) in 90 minutes. Synthesis raised score from 7→9 due to COMPOUND_TIDE_RAIN flag."*

No ML model produces this. This transparency is what earns operational trust.

