## 13. Prompt Engineering Specs

### 13.1 Shared Preamble (injected into all agent system prompts)

```
CONTEXT: You are operating as part of an automated flood prediction swarm
for Hong Kong. The current time is {HKT_TIMESTAMP}. Month: {MONTH}.
Season: {SEASON} (typhoon season = Jun–Nov).

CRITICAL RULES:
- Output ONLY valid JSON. No markdown, no prose outside JSON.
- Never hallucinate data. If a field is missing from input, state uncertainty
  in confidence score — do not invent a value.
- Confidence should reflect data quality, not your certainty about the world.
- risk_score of 10 should be rare — reserved for events that would trigger
  full emergency response.
```

### 13.2 Output Validation Strategy

Every LLM response is passed through a JSON schema validator before use. On schema validation failure:
- Retry once with `"Your previous response failed JSON schema validation. Error: {error}. Retry."` appended to the prompt
- On second failure: agent returns a default `UNKNOWN` signal with `confidence = 0.1`

### 13.3 Prompt Versioning

All system prompts are versioned as files in `prompts/`. Every `AgentSignal` includes the prompt version used, enabling A/B testing of prompt changes against historical events.

---

## 14. Key Design Decisions & Tradeoffs

| Decision | Rationale | Tradeoff |
|---|---|---|
| Parallel agent execution | Minimises latency to ~15s for the 5 specialist calls | Requires async orchestration; no sequential context sharing without peer queries |
| Separate CompoundDetector agent | Keeps specialist agents clean; compound logic is isolated and testable | One extra LLM call; adds ~15s latency |
| LLM for all reasoning (no hybrid ML) | Interpretability; no retraining; compound event handling; generalises to novel events | More expensive per run; LLM hallucination risk on edge cases |
| Three tide gauges | Covers all three HK flood zones; TBT critical for northern NT plains | More complex analysis; slight latency increase |
| Peer query protocol | Enables compound detection before synthesis; reduces synthesis workload | Adds latency for queries; complex timeout handling |
| Confidence-weighted synthesis | Degrades gracefully when data quality varies | Low-confidence agents still influence output; need tuning |
| Bilingual narrative | Operational necessity for HK emergency services | Doubles narrative generation time (mitigated: done in single synthesis call) |
| Separate system prompts per agent | Clear separation of concerns; easy to tune individual agents | Prompt drift if not versioned carefully |

